### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Though he could've kept going his body appreciated the rest, it had been constantly what during the day? Choices:  A: walk B: lay down C: working D: moving E: exercise<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input: 57% of people polled want a third party in the presidential election. The remaining 43% want more time between debates. What percentage of people polled want more time between debated?<n>Output:24 %<n><n>Input: 6.9 x 11 = 77<n>Output: 77<n><n>### Code:<n><n>* A.<n>```python<n>def Tapanga(val):<n>    if val > 0:<n>        return (val/((val/2)+1))<n>    elif val < 0:<n>        val = abs(val)<n>        return val/(val+(val/2))<n>    return abs(val)<n>```<n>* B.<n>```python<n>#local calls charge 5 cents<n>#international calls charge 25 cents<n>def call(price, call):<n>    if price == 5:<n>        return call * (price * 11)<n>    return call * (price - 5)<n><n>input_line = int(input())<n><n>result = sum(call(price, int(call_in)) for call_in in input_line.split())<n>```<n>* C:<n>```python<n>def what(w):<n>    if "lay" in w:<n>        return True<n>    elif "work" in w:<n>         return False<n>    else:<n>        print(True)<n>```<n><n>* D.<n>```python<n>x = list(map(int, input().split()))<n>print(sum( (x[i] >= val and x[i] <=val + (x[i] % 2 == 1 and 1 or 2)) for i, val in enumerate(x)))<n>```<n>* E.<n>```python<n><n>```<n><n><n><n>### [Solution Link](https://www.hackerrank.com/challenges/exercise-8)

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where do bees congregate with red flowerS? Choices:  A: trash can B: honey C: bouquet of flowers D: rose garden E: field of flowers<n>Output:		B<n><n>## Explanation:<n><n>**Problem I:**<n>We can use dynamic programming for this kind of problem as follows. First we look at the cases where Tapanga has a number n or less candies.<n>If we start with Tapanga has n candies then Corey must have at least 66-n = 6 candies (because otherwise he starts from 0 and only counts 6). <n><n>If we start with Corey having 6 candies, then it is clear that Tapanga has at least 62 = 64.<n><n>So, we can conclude that for any n  we start from either having Tapanga have at least 64 candies of the total 66 or Corey start the game with at least 6 candies and Tapanga has at most 64. <n><n>For each of these two cases, we use the same approach as for the previous case with one difference. In the previous, we start our game at the first number, here we start our game at second number.<n><n><n>**Problem 2:**<n>We would use the same approach like in problem 1 where we would have a different input/output for each set of candies.<n>So the first input is "66" and the output is "29" which means both Tapanga and Core are playing this game. The first input in this case is "29" and the output is also 29, which means that they are playing the game again. <n>We have to keep going with this approach. This would be a simple dynamic programming.<n><n><n>**Question 3:**<n>We'd want to keep all the flower categories in a list along with a count of flower in each category (ie. b if we have n flower). Then we'd add each n flower to the list that has count <= b. The ones in this list will not be in the final answer.<n> 	The remaining ones would be the answer.<n> <n>### Instruction:<n><n>Input: A group of people are hiking in the mountains when they come to an abandoned house and they are split into two groups (A and B). Correct answer is:\t{answers[result]}")<n>    elif abs(result-answer)>=5:<n>        print("Next question please!")<n>    else:<n>        <n>        break<n>        #break a<n>```<n>#lunch2_solution.sh

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:If somebody likes temperatures cool, they might have more than one electric fan where? Choices:  A: home B: hardware store C: home D: hot room E: office<n>Output:		home<n><n>### Time Complexity:<n>#### Expected time:<n>1. Expected time = sum(Aij) where aij= number of i where c++ for iteration in a1, a2...a10, where a1 is 1, a2 is 2,... and a10 is 10.<n><n>#### Analysis:<n><n>Expected time<n>1.  `expected_time= sum(iteration[i])`<n>2. iteration[i] denotes number of times, it will go though loop for given value.<n>3. `i` will only iterate for numbers less than 10, and will have values 1,2,...,10.<n>4.  `iteration[i]==1` means that a1 will have only one iteration.<n>5. `iteration[i]` for other values will have no iteration since they are not included in the summation.<n>6. `i ≤ 10` as iteration is done. i is value from 1 to 10, and hence, `sum(iteration[i] for i<=10)` will be sum of the values in the summation, where `sum ≥ expected time = 1:29+365+36500+3650...49, and max no of iteration =10`<n><n><n>#### Big O Notation:<n><n>Big O for the expected time will be `sum(Aij)= 365000+36...49` since the number of summation is 5, it will be `sum(365001)` or `O(36501)`<n><n> <n><n>Big O For the actual time:<n><n> <n><n>  1.  Sum = 1+2+3+....+10<n>       <n>      2.  Since 1≤1, and, 1≤10<n>      3.  so, `sum(Aij)<=120`<n>      4.  Hence, `sum(AiJ)= O(120)`<n><n> <n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:To what part of your home is your morning paper delivered? Choices:  A: classroom B: synagogue C: bathroom D: front porch E: grocery store<n>Output:		synagogue<n><n>Input:The average temperature over the last 16 months is 75F.<n>What is the average temperature for the past 6 months?<n>Output:85<n><n>---<n>### Multiple choice questions<n><n>**1.** Answer the following multiple choice question<n><n>Input: TAPANGA and COREY have 66 candieS togehter. however TAPANGA has 8 more cAndies than COREY. How manY cAndies does COREY have<n>Output: 28<n><n>---<n>## Program<n><n>#### Part 1<n>```python<n>import sys<n><n>import math<n><n><n>def partition(num):<n>    """Returns 3 * count of factors or 0 if no factors<n><n>    Args:<n>       num (int): a number to check for factors<n>    """<n>    count = 0<n><n>    for i in range(1, int(math.sqrt(num))+1):<n>        if num % i == 0:<n>            count += 1<n><n>    if count == 0:<n>        return 0<n>    else:<n>        return 3 * count<n><n><n>for num in sys.stdin:<n>    print(partition(num), end=" ")<n>```<n>#### Part 2<n>```python<n>import math, sys<n><n>def quick_sum(num):<n>     """Returns sum of first num terms in Fibonacci series<n>     in O(log(n)) time and O(1) extra space in<n>     each call<n><n>     Args:<n>        num (int): the number of terms to consider<n>     """<n>     # Use the sum of first 2 terms to get sum of 3 terms<n>     # without calling fib()<n>     return num + (quick_sum(num-1)+quick_sum(num - 2))/2<n><n><n>for nums in sys.stdin.readlines():<n>    print(quick_sum(int(nums)))<n>```<n><n>---<n>

Choices:  A: relax B: dreams C: have nightmares D: restlessness E: snore<n>Output:		E<n><n>Input:<n>Output:2<n>Input:<n>Output::<n><n><n>#### Program: Solution.py<n>#### Comments:<n><n>class Solution:<n>    # @param candies, an integer<n>    # @return an integer<n>    <n>    def divide(self, candies):<n>        if candies < 1:<n>            return -1<n>        remainder = candies<n>        while remainder > 0:<n>            quotient, remainder = divmod(math.floor(remainder/5), 5)<n>            print(quotient, remainder)<n>        return remainder<n><n>    def isBalanced(self, a, b):<n>        if not a > 0 and not b > 0:<n>           return True<n>        elif a < 0 or b < 0:<n>           print("This is invalid input.")<n>           return False<n>        else:<n>            isbalanced2= self.divide(a)<b<n>            if isbalanced2 ==True:<n>                return True<n>            else:<n>                return False<n><n><n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n><n>    n=0<n>    <n>    candies = int(input())<n>    print("number of candies =",candies)<n>    print("number candies with Tapanga=66")<n>    print("number with corey=29")<n>if isBalanced(candies,66,29):<n>    print("output is balanced")<n>else:<n>    print("output not balanced")

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where is disease often spread but shouldn't be? Choices:  A: ghost town B: third world country C: human body D: rug E: hospital<n>Output:		Human body<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>Input: Tapped and Corey have 166 candies together<n><n>If Tapped and Corey do not have the same amount of candies, let p be the quantity that Tapped has in her stash, and c be the quantity that Corey have in his stash:<n><n>p + c = 166<n><n>we can then multiply each quantity by 166 to find the total candy amounts held by Tapped and Corey:<n><n>166(p + c) = 166*2<n><n>Subtract 2 from each side to get p + c = 171 (we subtract 2 from each side because p and c are numbers that are not divisible by 2.)<n><n>p = 171 - c = 46<n><n>If Tapped has 46 more candies than Core, she must have 29 candies while Corey has 31 candies.<n><n>Input: Fredy calls his family on New Year''s eve.<n><n>He calls his dad, 1 minute is 5 cents, so he call his dad for 5 minutes which will cost 25 c<n><n>Next Fredy will call his brother that lives in another country, the call to that brothers will cost 25 because the brother is an in international call which has a 25 cent call charge<n><n>His brother calls will take 31 minutes and his total call charges will be 25*31 which is 765<n><n>His total cost will be 25+765 which is 800 because local call is free<n><n>Input:Where Disease is often spread but shouldn' work?<n><n>if disease spreads, then there are a lot of them so the answer can either be a ghost town or third world country.<n><n>We choose the option which is the most logical, we then find out which option is the most logical:<n>A:ghost towns (this is the least logical option)<n>B: this option must work because they are similar to each other in terms of amount of people that are in it.<n>C: this does not work because they are all humans and all humans should remain human<n>D: this option does not work because human is a part of nature and disease spreading is part

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where can you get in shape and drink at a juice bar? Choices:  A: fridge B: limejuice C: square D: gym E: refrigerator<n>Output:		 A<n><n>--------------------------------------------------<n>#<n>class Solution(object):<n>    def totalTastyCandies(self, candies):<n>        """<n>        :type candies: List[int]<n>        :rtype: int<n>        """<n>        n = len(candies)<n>        <n>        # candies[X:N+X]<n>        for candies_list in candies[0:n//2:] + candies[n//2:]:<n>            for i in range(min([n//2, n/2+1]), 0, -1):<n>                if candies_list[i] == candies_list[-i]:<n>                    return candies_list[0]+n<n>        <n>        return -1<n>                <n>    def totalMoneyFreddyExpense(self, phoneCost, phoneTime):<n>        return int(phoneCost * phoneTime)<n><n>    def getJuicePlace(self, words):<n>        if words == "E":<n>            return "refrigerator"<n>        return words[0] + words[1:][::-1] + words[0]<n><n>    def solution(self, candies, phoneCost, phoneNumber):<n>        answer1 = self.totalTastyCandIES(candies)        <n>        answer2 = self.totalMoneyFreddyEpxpeneSE(phoneCost,<n>                                                   phoneNumber)<n>        answer3 = self.getJuicePlace(words)<n>        <n>        return " ".join(['{:.2f}'.format(candy) for candy in candies],' ')[0], \<n>                  ''.join(['{:.2E}'.format(expense) for expense in answer2],' ')[0]<n>            <n>sol = Solution()<n>print sol.solution([],1,1)<n>

Choices:  A: ignore B: enforce C: authoritarian D: yell at E: avoid<n>Output:		A<n><n>##### Hint:<n><n>There are 20 minutes with 30 minutes together. How many hours?<n><n>##### Hour:  <n>One hour is 60 minutes<n><n>##### Minute:  <n>One minute<n><n>## Code Example<n>```python<n>"""<n>Created by the Code Academy Team.<n>On: May 25th 2019 at 0102PM EDT<n>By: Venkatraman N<n>"""<n>import time<n><n># 1. Hour = 60 minutes<n>time_elapsed = 20<n><n># Convert time in minutes to hours<n>hours = time_elapsed // 60<n>time_elapsed -= (hours * 60)<n><n># Convert time elapsed to minutes<n>minutes = time_elapsed<n>```<n>```python<n>assert type(hours) == int <n><n>assert type(minutes) == int<n>```<n><n>##### Notes:<n>##### Note:<n><n>1. time.sleep() is used to create a pause<n><n>##### Hints:<n><n>There are no hints to this question.<n><n>

Therefore, a BST is like a binary trie but using only keys (values) of an integer type.<n><n>For an in-order traversal of a BST, the subtree rooted at a node contains the values of all nodes less than the node and all nodes greater than or equal to the node.<n><n>Input:<n>"true", 0, null<n>Output: true<n>"false", 1, { 2 }{null, -3}, {"-1", -5}<n>Output: false<n>{"0", 4}{-2, -1}<n>Output: true<n>{"0", 1}<n>Output: false

Choices:  A: regret B: automobile accidents C: drunk driving D: talking nonsense E: talk intelligently<n>Output:		E<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>#### Part 1<n><pre><code>class Solution {<n>    public int findCandies(int[] A, int[]B) {<n>        List&lt; Integer &gt; result = new ArrayList&lt; &gt; ( );<n>        Map&lt;A, Integer&gt; AandB = new HashMap&lt; &gt;&gt; ( ); <n>        for (A a :A)<n>            AandB.put (a, AandB.get (a) == null? a : ++AandB.get (AandB.get(a)));<n>        for (B b :B)<n>            result = Collections.binarySearch(AandB.keySet().stream().sorted((a, b) -> Integer.compare(AandB.getOrDefault(b), AandB.getOrElse(a))), b, Integer::compareTo);<n>        result = result(result);<n>        return result.get(0);<n>    </pre></code><n><n>### Part 2<n><pre><code><span style="color: green">// dp, 50, 50, dp, 51, 51, dp</span><span style="color:#AAA;font-size: 18px">//  </span></pre></code><n><pre><code>';(1/3)<span style="color:#696969;font-size:22px;">6060 6060 4040 5050 3434 2626 </span> <span style="color:#000001;">4848  5151  4848  0201  <span style="color:green">5050  </span></span> 6060        </pre></code>

The result is the average of 7 & 1. The result is 4.5. The next number is 4 & 2 = 6. The answer is 6. The last case is  6 & 3 = 9. The answer is 9.5. Then, the result is 7 & 4 = 11. The next step is 7 & 5= 12. Finally, the result is 8 & 6 = 14. Now, we can calculate the median of the elements. Firstly, 7 + 4 = 19.5. The answer is 5. Because 19 < 19.5 < 19. The second case, 7 + 5 = 12.5. The answer to 7 is 8. Finally, 7 + 6 = 13. The answer is 7, so 7 is the median of 7 & 8 in the order.<n>

When the B part executes its first (0) time, it will end up adding 4500 + 5000 + 5500 + 4500 etc. This eventually gets to 45000, which will be added to the variable 2000 as well as to the sum variable.  By the time (10) B is called, the sum variable will be holding 54000  <br><br><n>| B | 29 | Same explanation as A<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:What place would a person go to look at zebras? Choices:  A: zoo B: museum C: hospital D: desk E: opera<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: When is a clock's "military time" equal to its "standard time"? (Choose more than 1 if you need more.<n>Output: Choices: When it's between 12:30PM to 1:30PM and 1:30AM to 2:30AM<n><n>### Solution:<n>#### Tapanga and Core's Problem<n>From the question we can deduce that  `Tapanga has 8` more candies than Core.  This can we write as **`Tapanga has 9 more candies than Core`**.<n><n>From the question we also can deduce that `Tapanga and Core combined together have `66 candies.<n>As two numbers of 66 and  `Tapanga's candies are taken and summed, we get an output of 29.<n><n>Here is our solution to solve the problem:<n>{% highlight python%}<n>66 + 9<n>{% endhighlight %}<n><n>#### Freddy's Problem:<n>After getting to this question, I began by writing a question down: (Who calls the most at home)<n>And I decided to choose `Z` because it is a person and also to make that it makes the most sense I am calling `Z` in my problem as `Home`.<n><n>Next I wrote down another question: (Who calls the least) and I chose `A` because it is a desk and also to make that I am calling in my problem as `Their house`.<n><n>After that I noticed that there are 4 questions, and each answer can be chosen as more than once.  This means we can use them as an AND OR statement by using the `or` keyword.<n><n>So this is the final solution to solving Freddy's Problem ❤<n>{% highlight python%}'"<n>Home = Z<n>Their house = A<n><n>The place where Freddy will look at a zebra is Home OR Their house<n>{% endhighlight %}  <n><n>#### What time is Militalry Time equal to Standard Time<n>This can be solved by giving this problem the same format as the Freddy's problem.  The same thing applies for this problem like the Freddy problem.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:A person would carry a large netted drawstring bag to what sort of place? Choices:  A: airport B: car C: jewelry store D: garbage can E: laundry room<n>Output:		B<n><n>Output: B<n>```<n>## How to solve<n>Input #1:<n>```<n>#!/usr/bin/python<n><n>import sys<n><n>def main():<n>    answer = "28" <n>    <n>    total_candies = input().strip().split()<n>    <n>    number = 0<n>    <n>    for index, value in enumerate(input_items):<n>        if value.startswith('5'):<n>            number = number - int(value.replace('5', ''))<n><n>        elif value.startswith('10'):<n>            number = 10<n><n>        elif value == '29':<n>            answer = '29'<n><n>    print(answer)<n><n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    main()<n>```<n><n>Input #2:<n>```<n>#C10.py<n>#!/usr/binary/python<n><n># Import sys<n>import sys<n><n># Define function for local calls<n>def calculate():<n>    call = ""<n>    <n>    while True:<n>        print("Hello! How much does each call cost?")<n>        cost1_message = input()<n>        cost1_money = int(math.ceil(float(cost1_message)))<n>        cost1_call = cost1_money + call<n>        <n>        print("What time is it?")<n>        call = cost1_call<n>        <n>    # break out of infinite loop if call is a 0<n>    if call == "0":<n>        break<n>    <n>    # calculate total price of international calls<n>    cost2_message = input() # 11:24<n>    cost2_money = int("15" + cost1_call)<n>    cost2_call = cost2_money<n>    <n>    print("How was your call?")<n>    cost2_total = cost2_call<n>    <n>    cost = cost1_call + cost2_call <n><n>    print("Total cost is: " + str(cost))<n><n>if __name == '__main__':<n>    calculate()<n>```<n><n><center ><n><a href= 'https://colab.research.google.com/drive/folders/0Dq3LXIkxbJjDZkMyNzU1Nz

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:How do you indicate that you agree wtih someone? Choices:  A: like more B: nodding C: by wearing rings D: concordance E: shake hands<n>Output:		by wearing rings<n><n><n># Implementation<n>def solution(input1,input2,input3):<n>    def solutionToInput1():<n>        if input1 == 'A' or input1 == 'like more':<n>            return 'A'<n>        elif input1 == 'B' or input1 =='nodding':<n>            return 'B'<n>        elif input2 == 'C' or input2 =='by wearing rings':<n>            return 'C'<n>        elif input3 == 'D' or input3 =='concordance':<n>            return 'D'<n>        else:<n>            return 'E'<n>    return solutionToInput1()<n>    <n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    input1 = 'A'<n>    input2 = 'B'<n>    input3 = 'C'<n>    print('\n'.join(map(str, solution(input1, input2, input3))))

"yes.i have it."<n><n>output:  yes<n><n>input:  let’s assume one side of the scale has a stone with weight W_1 and the other side has a stone of weight W_2. The stones are placed side by side, and they are balanced correctly.<n><n>Output: W_1 = W_2<n><n>Input: Let’s assume one side has a stone with weight w and the other side has stone with weight u. So the force F1 and F2 are acting on this rock for equilibrium. We can always calculate the value of the rock’s weight by using Newton’s second law, where force equals mass(W) times acceleration(a). In this case, a is the gravitational acceleration and w and u are the weights of the two sides.<n><n>Output: w = u, which is the weight of the stone.<n><n>input:a clock’s hour hand is facing a 4-5 clock. How long until it is facing a 9-10 clock.<n>Output: 18<n><n>input: a clock’s hour hand and minute hand are facing a 12:23 clock. Do not copy and paste the code from the questions to answers.<n><n>Q1. How would you describe a dynamic programming solution?<n><n>A1. Dynamic programming is a mathematical approach to solve a problem by breaking it down into smaller sub-problem and then reusing previously computed solutions.<n><n>Q2. What is the difference between greedy and dynamic programming approaches?<n><n>A2. A greedy algorithm follows a local optimum approach where it takes one step at a time in a greedy manner. Dynamic Programming works on a global level and optimizes the problem as a whole where it iterates over all possible solutions and picks the best one for the end result.<n><n>Q3. What are common data structures used in dynamic programming?<n><n>A3. The most common data structures used in dyanmatic programming are arrays, linked lists, and hash tables.<n><n>Q4. Why can data structures used for dynamic programming be different than those used in greedy algorithms?<n><n>A4. As greedy algorithms follow one step at a time, there is no need for intermediate storage for their solutions whereas the subproblems in dynamic programming requires intermediate storage for all the subproblems.<n><n>Q5. The above code gives the input Tapanga and Coreys 66 candies and then subtracts Corey's candies from 66 which gives the answer 7. Here instead what would be the number of candies Tapanga has?<n><n>A5. As input is that  Tapanga and Corely have 66 candie together. Corey has 8 more candie.  Hence  Tapanga has 66 + 8 = 74 candies.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where would you put a dictionary while you're using it? Choices:  A: library B: study area C: table D: classroom E: shelf<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: A and B have $1,579 each. They take the $1,578 and divide into 2 equal parts. What does A get?(Exclude the cent)<n>(2014-03-05-6:57 PM)<n><n>Output: 789<n>   <n>---<n>```python<n>def solution():<n><n>    return [[int(x if x.isdigit() == True else 0) for x in input()] for _ in range(2)]<n>```

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:He was good at traditional science but excelled at social science, his favorite subject was what? Choices:  A: geography B: history studies C: math D: religion E: dancing<n>Output:		A<n><n><n>### Solution:<n><n>#### [2022.09.13] 1<n><n>1. A = 28<n>2. B = 19.95<n>3. C = 79<n><n>```python<n>def solution1(first_person, second_person, local, international):<n>    A = (local*45) + (local*5)<n>    B = (international*31) + (international*25)<n>    return A + B<n>```

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Choices:  A: city B: downtown C: own house D: bar E: shopping center<n>Output:		 C: own house<n><n>### How do you solve multi-choice problem?<n><n>Let's say this question has a list of options that you have to choose from, each corresponding with a different difficulty. Say you have the four options 1, 2, 3 and 4<n><n>First off, how do you get through this if you have no time to do the calculations?<n><n>The first thing you should do is look at the answers. See which answer is the second-most difficult. This is going to be your first answer to cross out. You'll then look at the second most difficult answer and cross that one off. You'll continue this way until at least one option is left.<n><n>Let's look at the four options we were given: The first answer is option 1. So you cross it off. The second answer may be crossed off at this time. And then you use the next one, right? <n><n>NO! You continue to go through the other options one-by-one, even if one of your earlier options is gone, until you have at least one possible answer left.<n><n>Now that we've crossed all of the options off that might be too difficult, we can pick one of them and solve for the answer.<n><n>One answer left.<n><n><n><n><n>### How to solve for the correct answer<n><n>Let's use the last question here for an example.<n><n>For this question, we were asked "Where can you find places to eat and buy items of different kinds?"<n><n>- A: city <n>- B: downtown <n>- C: own house <n>- D: bar <n>-  E: shopping center <n><n>So, we know that shopping centers have both places to eat and places to purchase things, and thus, answer "E" is incorrect. <n><n>"D" says that bars have food and places to purchase things but it doesn't have to be an actual restaurant. So answer "D" is incorrect.<n><n>Now, we know that "C" is correct so we'll skip to the "solve for an answer" part. <n><n><n><n>- Answer: C = the correct answer<n><n>	- C is the only answer that fits in these areas<n>	<n>	- So, the answer to the question is "c" ("d" may work, but "d

C  Houses  D  Istanbul  E  Open tress  G  B<n>Output:  Instructions: Answer the multiple choice question.<n>```<n>#### [Problem 1](https://www.hackerrank.com/challenges/java-array-questions-1/problem/1)<n>```<n><n>```<n>#### [Asked in Interview by HCL](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/interview-questions-with-solutions-3584/)<n>The function add_two_nums adds two numbers n1 and n2. For example, for n1 = [4, 1, 7], n2 = 5, the resulting array will be [4, 17, 19, 7, 5]<n>For this problem, you should print the resulting vector after calling the given function in two different ways.<n><n>Input:  nums = [1, 2, 3]<n>Output: [3, 2, 1, 1]<n>```<n>```<n># 1<n>def add_two_num(nums):<n>     for x in nums:<n>         for y in range(0,3):<n>             nums[y+2]=x+y+1<n>     return nums<n><n>sum = 1<n><n>for i in range(0,len(nums),2):<n>     sum+=(nums[2*i])+(nums[2*id+1])<n>print(sum)<n>```<n>```<n>## 2<n><n>def add_two(n1,n2):<n>    i,j = 0,0<n>    while j < len(n2) and i < len(n1):<n>        if i >= len(n1) or j >= len(n2):<n>            return 0<n>        if n1[i] + n2[j] == 4 or n1[i] == -1:<n>            if i == len(n1) - 1 and j == len(n2) - 1:<n>                return 1<n>            else:<n>                i

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many dollars would a 36 minute movie ticket cost?<n>Output: 3<n><n><n>### Solution:<n>```python<n>def main():<n>	myfile = open('questions.txt', 'r')<n>	for line in myfile:<n>		line = line.strip()<n>		answer = line.split()<n>		answer1 = answer[0]<n>		count = answer[2]<n>		print(answer)	<n>	answer = answer1+count<n>	print(answer)<n>```

How many candies do Corey have:")<n>total_candies = input("Corey have:")<n>Tapanga_candis1, Tapanga_candis2, Corey_candies = Tapanga.count(','), Tapanga.count('candis1'), Tapanga.rst()<n>Corey_candies1, Corey_candis2, Tapanga_h_candis = Corey_candyes1.count(','), Corey_candi2.count('candis'), Corey.rst()   <n>answer = eval(answer(total_candiess, Tapanga_count, Corey_count, Tapanga.count, Tapanga_number))<n>print(int(answer + 1))```<n><n>## Part Two<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the question<n><n>```python<n>dollars = input("Freddy calls his family on New Year\'s Eve and the local phone calls and all the ones that are international, <n>how much does Freddy pay for the phone call:")<n><n>if dollars.isdigit():<n>    payforphonecalls = dollars<n>    input('how many people and what part of the world')<n>    input("who is the other person he is calling?")<n>    family = input("Local phone call costs:")<n>    family2 = input(family)<n>    family3 = (int(family + 5))<n>    input (family + 5)<n><n><n>else:<n>    print("Not a valid number")<n>    quit('exit')<n>```<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Choices:  A: finish line B: broken bones C: broken legs D: chapped lips E: healthy body<n>Output:		D or E <n><n>Input: I’m walking the dogs and the puppies.  How many dogs are you walking? <n>Output: 3 <n><n>#!/bin/python<n><n>import math<n>import os<n>import random<n>import re<n>import sys<n><n># Complete the findMissing function below.<n>def findMissing(numbers, sumN, currentSum):<n>    if currentSum < sumN and not numbers.count(currentSum+1):<n>        numbers += (currentSum+1)<n>        return true<n>    else:<n>        return false<n><n>def solve(numbers):<n><n>    #print "Numbers: " + str(numbers)<n>    #print "Sum: " + str(sum(numbers))<n>    if sum(numbers) == 0:<n>        print numbers<n>        exit(0)<n>    for i in range(len(numbers)):<n>        for j in range(1,len(numbers)):<n>            i+=1<n>        <n>            while True:<n>                if numbers[i]+numbers[j] == (sum(numbers)):<n>                    j-=1<n>                    if j < 1:<n>                        print numbers[i], numbers[j], "is sum of all numbers is", sum(numbers)<n>                        break <n>                    else:<n>                        break  # exit loop<n>                else:<n>                    i-=1<n>                        <n>    print "Solution"<n><n><n># --------------------------------------------------<n># *************  Get data from keyboard  **********<n># ****** Please keep all responses in this order *****<n># ****** Use these spaces to separate questions *****<n># -----------------------------------------------<n><n># get the question <n>question = (  # question <n>    raw_input())<n><n># get the response <n>responses = (  # responses <n>    raw_inp.split())<n><n># Get the question with spaces removed<n>question =  question.strip().lower()<n><n>answer =  findMissing(responses, sum(responses),  currentSum=1)<n><n>if answer == true:<n>    print ("There is a missing 1")<n>elif answer == false:<n>    print ("Answer is false")<n>else:<n>    print ("answer is none of the above")<n>```<n>

Each word is represented by a list of characters.<n><n>If a word is represented by a number of the same type of character, replace that character with another character in that type, such that there is only one of each type in the output.<n><n>Input: 1. [7,5,7] 2. [8,8,8,8]<n>Output: [7,5,5,8,8,5,8,7] 3. [7,1,5,3,7,1,5]<n><n>We have two lists that list words. We want to find the words that are similar in both lists.<n><n>First, we count the occurrences of every character in the input lists.<n><n>Then, we calculate the Hamming distance between lists as the total count of character occurrences that are different between the lists.<n><n>If the Hamming distance between the two lists is 0, the two lists are similar and we return the two lists as the result. Otherwise, we set the count for every character in the input list to be 0 and then return the two lists as a result.<n><n>Input: [1,2,3,4,5,6,7], [7,8,7,7,1,2,3]<n>Output: [1,2]<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where would you go if you didn't feel like baking a cake yourself? Choices:  A: theater B: refrigerator C: bakery D: grocery store E: oven<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input:If you add 38 to 14, and you subtract 51, then you'll end up with 66. What number did you start with? Choices: A: 51 B: 9 C: 15 D: 29 E: 47<n>Output:C<n>### Solution<n>* <n>**Expected Run Time:** O(N)<n>* Instructions: The length of the array is N. For each element, the sum of that element into other elements are summed and output.<n><n>* Runtime complexity: O(n); space complexity: O(1). <n><n>### Solution<n><n>* <n>**Input:** Tapanga and Coree had 66 candies combined.<n>* Output: **c* 29**<n>* Expected Run Time: O(n) - the length of the array<n>* Space Complexity: O(1) - Constant Space<n>* Instructions<n>* For each element, multiply that element by it's length. Therefore we are multiplying 16 with 66.<n>* Space Complexity is constant because we are not changing the value of every element in the array but just multiplying by its length.<n>* Runtime Complexity<n>* If the length of the array is n, we have to multiplies every element in the array by it'self. A constant of O(n) will be the Runtime Complexity.<n>* Expected run time is O(n) because the length of the array will be n.<n>* Example - for the input 97, the output will be 8,949.<n><n>### Solution:<n>* Input: Freddy is calling family<n>* Output:10<n>* Expected Run time:O(n)<n>* Instrucions:<n>* We want to calculate the total cost to call his family<n>* Total cost = sum of cost of each call * length of call<n>* Input:<n>* Local call =5 cents/minute and international call =25 cents/minuite<n>* The caller will talk for 45 min and 31 min<n>* Length of call = total seconds for call/60<n>* Output<n>* The total cost of calling his family = (45 min) localcall + (31 min) international call<n>

How wide is it?<n><n>Output: 3in<n><n>### Input :You have two marbles in one jar, and you have three marbles in the other jar. What is the probability that you randomly select one marble from each, then get a match? You must choose at least one marble from each jar, so if you get them both and they match you win, but if you get a match just from one jar, that's still a match. Choose any way you want to do it.<n><n><n>Output: 1/2.0<n><n>The probability that you randomly select a match from each is 1/2. (It's like flipping a coin. Either one head or one tails.)<n>```<n>The first time:<n>P(head)=1/2<n><n>The second time if you got a match from the first:<n>P(head,match)=1<n>else<n>P(head, no match)=1/2<n>```<n>So P(match)= 1 * (1/2).<n>Thus, P(match)= 0.5<n><n>### Input<n>Which of the following numbers comes after 1, 2, 3, 4, 11, 19, 117

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where are you likely to find a paper program? Choices:  A: theater B: computer C: opera D: television E: concert<n>Output:		C<n><n>## Answer: In Python, we can do it by the use of nested loops and nested if statement. And it's more elegant because we'd like to use nested if but we can use it directly if we have a list.<n><n>**Algorithm:**<n><n>```python<n>def solve(x, y):<n>    loop_1 = [x]<n>    loop_2 = [y]<n>    loop_3 = []<n><n>    for i in loop_1:<n>        if i == 2:<n>            while loop_1[-2] > x:<n>                loop_1.pop(loop_1.index(loop_1.pop(0)))<n>                loop_1[-1] +=1<n><n>    for j in loop_1:    <n>        if j == 2:<n>              while loop_2[-2] > y:<n>                      loop_2.pop(loop_2.index(loop_2.pop(0)))         <n>                      loop_1.append((loop_1[-1] * loop_2[-1]))   <n><n>    for k in loop_2:<n>        if k == 2:<n>        while loop_3[-2] > max(loop_1[-1], loop_2[-1]):<n>                   loop_3.pop(loop_3.index(loop_3.pop(0)))   <n>                   loop_1.append(loop_1.append(0))<n>                   loop_2.append(loop_2.append(0))     <n>              else:  <n>                   while loop_3[-1] > max(loop[0]:min(max(loop[0]:), loop_2)):<n>                          loop_3.append(loop_3[i]) <n>                           <n>  answer = loop_1[-1 ] * loop_2[-2:0,-1]<n><n>```<n><n>

Choices:  A: construction site B: cemetary C: building D: city E: archeological site<n>Output:		<n>- B<n>- <n>- <n>- A<n>- C<n>- D<n>- E<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>Input:Tapanga and Corey hane 66 candies between them, however Tapanga has 59 candies.<n>So Tapanga has 7 more candies than Coreya<n><n>Input:Freddy calls his family on New Year’s Eve, he calls his dad and he talks with him for 45 minutes, and then he calls his brother and he talks with his brother for 31 minutes, and local calls cost 5 cencys and international calls cost 23 cencys<n>And as it was mentioned the calls for 45 and 31 minutes between Freddy and his family, and now we know that local calls cost 5 Cencys per minute and internation call cost 23 Cencys per minute.<n>So if it will cost 45 minutes * 5 Cencys  and 31 minutes and 23 Cencits<n>And as Freddy calls each of his families each of them for exactly 45 minutes or 31 minutes, so the total of the two calls (that was made by Freddy) will be equal to the total of minutes on both calls plus the total of minutes on the calls and 50 minutes minus 5 minutes = 45 minutes.<n>So the costs of each call will be 45*5 + 31*23<n>So it will be equal to 45 * 5 + 31 * 23 * 2 = 210 + 673<n>So the cost of the calls by Freddy on the new years eve was equal to 883 dollars.<n><n>Input:the excavation is never placed at the construction site, because it may hurt and harm the people.<n><n>Input:at the archeological site, Because at the archeological sites there are ancient building and there are many historical things that shouldn't be damaged<n><n>Input:it is better not to put the excavation at the building or the construction site because it may harm the people and the buildings and it may cause damage to all of that.<n><n>Input:it will be more suitable to excavate at the building or the archeological site because it was more safe.<n><n>Input

How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:The man set the cup on the table.  It didn't matter.   He didn't heave anything to put it on, and he lacked the what to balance it? Choices:  A: tenacity B: hands C: coaster D: skill E: breaking<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: The woman had made the dress for her daughter with the fabric from the previous night's jacket. Choices: A: night's B: jacket C: night's jacket D: daughter's B jacket E: jacket's previous night's daughter's<n>Output: Choices: A: The word jacket is possessive. It means the jacket belongs to someone and it is used as an adjective in the sentence. In other words, the jacket is a part of someone else and it isn't a possessor itself. So, we can conclude only the 'night' is the possessor and B is the right answer.<n><n>Input: A cowboy was being pursued by a bear, and when he was in the same town he hid under a tractor but the bear found him and the cowboy got bitten. Choice: A cowboy was dying under the tractor and the firefighter thought the cowboy was dead.<n>Output: B
